         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="vol-2-P_M-d2e2255-person" n="vol-2-P_M-Elijah-7">
               <sex cert="high">M</sex>
               <persName type="lemma">אליהו<ref corresp="#d2e1954"/>
               </persName>
               <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Elijah</persName>
               <persName xml:lang="gr"><ref corresp="#d52e5"/>
               </persName>
               <persName xml:lang="checkme"/>
               <state type="desc">
                  <note>Official<ref corresp="#d2e2268"/>
                  </note>
               </state>
               <state type="provenance">
                  <note>Boundary stone, Abel Beit Ma‘akha<ref corresp="#d2e2279"/>
                  </note>
               </state>
               <bibl>Offord,PEFQS40 (1908) 260</bibl>
               <state type="addl-Descr">
                  <note>Jew?<ref corresp="#d2e2292"/>
                  </note>
               </state>
               <floruit>293-305<ref corresp="#d2e2303"/>
               </floruit>
               <note xml:id="d2e2261" n="16"> See below, n. 27. </note>
               <note xml:id="d2e2268" n="17"> In Greek – <span xml:lang="checkme"></span>
                            (stewardship of Elius Magistrate – Offord’s translation). On this title
                            see Introduction 3.1.3.4.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e2279" n="18">
                            In north Israel, on the source of the Jordan river.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e2292" n="19"> The inscription is dated to the time of
                            Diocletian. A person named Elijah under his anti-Christian rule would
                            have been Jewish, see vol. 3, Introduction 6.6, pp. 50-1. However, this
                            was the name of an administrative official, and it may not have been a
                            rendition of Elijah, but rather of a Greek name, see e.g. WGE. 348-9.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e2303" n="20"> The stone refers to the Diocletian at the time he
                            assumed with Maximinus the title Augustus. These are the dates when this
                            title would have been relevant, see Introduction 7.1.</note>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
